Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1990, East and West Germany celebrate ‚ÄúUnity Day‚Äù less than a year after the Berlin Wall's fall, marking their reunification after being separated for 45 years. 

Since 1945, Germany had been divided into an eastern Communist zone and a western Allied-controlled zone, symbolizing the Cold War's tensions. Key events, like the Berlin Blockade (1948-1949) and the wall's construction in 1961, highlighted this division. As Soviet power declined in the late 1980s, the East German Communist Party weakened, leading to mass emigration and the wall's eventual dismantling in late 1989. Reunification talks followed, involving officials from both German states and major Allied powers. Just two months later, Germany held its first all-German elections, resulting in Helmut Kohl becoming the first chancellor of a reunified nation. 

Although the Soviet Union would not dissolve for over a year, many viewed Germany's reunification as a pivotal moment signaling the Cold War's end.

Name: Graham, Lindsey
text:
This is the 1930's all over again. G7 leaders  ‚Äì  led by President Biden ‚Äì are urging Israel to have a proportional and limited response against the Iranian regime.

Apparently the G7 views Iran as a normal nation. It is not.

I have been working with President Biden and his team for over a year and a half to achieve normalization between Saudi Arabia and Israel ‚Äì building on the Abraham Accords brokered by President Trump.  This would be a historic shift in the Middle East. I believe the October 7 attack by Hamas  ‚Äì  financed and supported by Iran  ‚Äì  was designed to stop this process. I will continue to push for normalization.

When it comes to Iran, the regime is a theocracy dedicated to destroying the Jewish state, driving the west out of the Middle East, and stopping reconciliation between the Arab world and Israel. The Ayatollah is a religious Nazi. Iran is not trying to build peaceful nuclear power plants. The regime is trying to build a nuclear bomb to achieve its religious objectives. If you don‚Äôt understand that, you‚Äôre not listening to what Iran is saying and you‚Äôre not watching what they are doing throughout the world.

For the sake of our friends in Israel, we cannot allow the world to miscalculate Iran, just as it did with Hitler and the Nazis.

I truly believe if Iran had a nuclear weapon, the Ayatollah would use it against Israel.

The idea of telling Israel what targets to strike ignores reality and is the mentality that existed in the 1930‚Äôs.

Would a proportional response be launching 200 ballistic missiles from Israel into Iran, mimicking what the Iranians did to Israel?

To my friends in Israel, one holocaust directed at the Jewish people is enough. Do what you have to do to defend yourselves against those who would kill you simply because you are Jewish.

https://t.co/yqAZ6i5n0o

Name: Scott, Rick
text:
While I appreciate President Biden, USDA Secretary Tom Vilsack and officials from FEMA coming to Florida to see the damage here firsthand, there is so much work to be done. During my meeting with President Biden, I stressed that the federal government‚Äôs response to hurricanes over the last two years has left too many Floridians, especially our farmers, hurting and with unmet needs ‚Äì and this must be fixed NOW. It is going to take local, state and federal efforts to help communities recover along the Gulf Coast. That‚Äôs why I‚Äôve demanded that Majority Leader Chuck Schumer immediately reconvene the Senate once FEMA and the SBA finalize damage assessments so we can fully fund these agencies, the USDA, and others responding to this disaster with a clean disaster supplemental appropriations bill. I‚Äôll be fighting like hell to deliver disaster aid to our state, and ensure seamless debris removal guidance for our local communities, and I urged the federal officials there today to put Floridians and all Americans first by doing the same. Since Hurricane Ian, Washington has played games with disaster relief funds and delayed the delivery of urgently needed FEMA assistance, and other aid like USDA block grants for Florida‚Äôs farmers and my Federal Disaster Tax Relief Act. This aid has been routinely provided to victims of hurricanes in the past but that has not been the case since Hurricanes Ian, Debby and Idalia and that must change so we can deliver this aid NOW.

Hurricane Helene devastated communities along hundreds of miles of Florida‚Äôs Gulf Coast and caused unimaginable damage and loss in Taylor County and across the Big Bend. Since the days before the storm, I‚Äôve visited impacted communities in 11 counties to meet with local and state officials and hear what they need from the federal government, and been in constant contact with state and federal officials to coordinate resources. Floridians are resilient, but recovery doesn‚Äôt fall just on these families ‚Äì it‚Äôs an all hands on deck operation that requires the federal government to show up today, tomorrow and every day until the job is done and I won‚Äôt stop fighting to make sure that happens.

Name: Timmons, William R.
text:
Today Upstate officials received a briefing from Adjutant General McCarty of the South Carolina National Guard. He reported that nearly 1,000 SC National Guard soldiers and airmen are deployed in South Carolina to get resources to those in need here in the Upstate area as well as to our neighbors in Western NC. 

We have chainsaw crews assisting local authorities here in SC and a joint air lift operation taking resources to those hit hardest in North Carolina. If you see the CH-47 Chinooks flying overhead, know they are full of sorely needed supplies and heading to our friends in the Asheville area. They are providing much needed hope to those impacted even worse. 

I am grateful for all the tireless work they are doing to help us recover from this devastating storm. And while things may be uncomfortable for those still without power (of which I am one), we should all remember how fortunate we are to be safe. If you do have urgent needs, county emergency managers are here to meet them. 

The power will come back on soon. South Carolina is strong and resilient. We have a long road to recovery, but we will move past this.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1957, the Space Age begins with the launch of Sputnik, the first artificial satellite, by the Soviet Union. 

The satellite launched from the Tyuratam launch base in Kazakhstan. Weighing 184 pounds and measuring 22 inches in diameter, Sputnik orbited Earth every hour and 36 minutes at a speed of 18,000 miles per hour. It transmitted radio signals that could be received by amateur radio operators in the U.S., sparking both fascination and concern over Soviet technological advancements.

Launched to coincide with the International Geophysical Year, Sputnik‚Äôs success prompted fears in the U.S. about potential military applications of Soviet rocket technology, especially as it was significantly larger than the planned U.S. satellite, Explorer, which launched in January of 1958. The launch of Sputnik marked the beginning of the space race, as the U.S. government and military scrambled to catch up.

In the following years, the Soviet Union achieved several space milestones, including the first living being in orbit, the first human in space, and numerous other firsts. However, the U.S. made a significant leap in 1969 with the Apollo 11 mission, successfully landing astronauts on the moon.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we celebrate the remarkable stories of Hometown Heroes from across our district. Today, it is with immense pride that we shine a spotlight on an extraordinary group of women whose legacy has not only shaped our past but continues to inspire our future. Meet this week‚Äôs Hometown Heroes‚Äîthe incredible women of PA-1 who answered our nation‚Äôs call as Rosie the Riveters during World War II.
 
When our country needed them most, these women‚Äîour mothers, grandmothers, sisters, and neighbors‚Äîrose to the occasion with unshakable courage and conviction. They rolled up their sleeves and got to work on factory floors, shipyards, and munitions plants, pouring their energy and spirit into the war effort. With every bolt tightened and every rivet placed, they laid the foundation for the America we know today, breaking down barriers, shattering stereotypes, and opening doors for future generations. The Rosies of PA-1 embodied the spirit of resilience, determination, and patriotism, showing the world that strength knows no bounds.
 
For far too long, their immense contributions went unrecognized, which is why I introduced the Rosie the Riveter Congressional Gold Medal Act‚Äîsigned into law in 2020‚Äîto ensure these trailblazers, who taught us all what We Can Do It truly means, received the long overdue honor they so richly deserve. 
 
This past weekend, I hosted a ceremony in our community to honor our remarkable Rosies. Surrounded by their families, we presented them with Congressional Gold Medals, citations, and American flags flown over the U.S. Capitol. It was a day filled with joy, reverence, and heartfelt remembrance. It was the honor of a lifetime to celebrate with our living Rosies, Rita Colella, Dorothy Trate, Michaeline Kryven, and Mae Krier, as well as with the families of the Rosies no longer with us: Pauline Biedka, Angela Calabrese, Virginia DiMaggio, Sarah Eglinger, Marion G. Gelb, Eunice Pearl Heath, Beverly Jean O‚ÄôBradovic, Angelina Romello, Barbara Roth, Alice K. Schafer, Mary Schaefer Simmons, Ann Meredith Smith, Eleanor Sladko Stern, Rose Sutor, and Doris Wiley McNichol. 
 
These PA-1 women didn‚Äôt just contribute to a war effort‚Äîthey forged a path for generations of women to follow. Their efforts ensured the torch of liberty would continue to burn bright, and their example inspires us to meet the challenges of our own time with the same resolve, determination, and love of country. The indomitable Rosies of Bucks and Montgomery Counties continue to remind us that when we come together with a shared purpose, there is no challenge we cannot overcome.
 
Please join me in celebrating these extraordinary women, thanking them for their sacrifice, their trailblazing spirit, and their enduring impact. The Rosies of PA-1 define what it means to be true Hometown Heroes, and their legacies will be forever etched into the history of our community and great nation.

This plan is inhumane. It would tear apart communities across the country, take parents away from their U.S. citizen kids, and remove children from classrooms.

But it would also be bad for America ‚Äî for our tax system, for our government programs, and for our economy as a whole.

Name: Jayapal, Pramila
text:
One of the most cruel and extreme portions of Trump‚Äôs Project 2025 is his plan for mass deportations ‚Äî a scheme to build detention camps and rip apart millions of families. It‚Äôs unconscionable.

Let‚Äôs talk about it. üßµ

Name: Jayapal, Pramila
text:
Now, let‚Äôs talk about the economic impacts.

Mass deportations could cause the U.S. economy to lose between 4.2% to 6.8% in GDP ‚Äî more than the 4.3% loss in the 2008 Recession.

In 20 years, the U.S. economy could shrink by 6% ‚Äî or $1.6 trillion.

Name: Jayapal, Pramila
text:
Let‚Äôs begin with the actual process of deporting millions of individuals ‚Äî a process that Trump has given zero specifics about.

If it were to happen, removing America‚Äôs undocumented population would be incredibly harmful and costly.

Name: Jayapal, Pramila
text:
If Trump implemented a mass deportation plan that removed 1 million people per year, it would cost $88 billion annually ‚Äî more than DHS's entire budget!

That money could go toward education, health care, housing ‚Äî instead, Trump wants to use it for his xenophobic pet project.

Name: Jayapal, Pramila
text:
Why would that happen?

Because undocumented immigrants fill millions of jobs across the country. They grow and harvest our food, they build our homes and office buildings, and they care for our kids and our seniors.

They are NECESSARY.

Name: Jayapal, Pramila
text:
Undocumented immigrants also pay taxes ‚Äî in 2022, they paid $96.7 billion in federal, state, and local taxes.

Mass deportation would mean the U.S. would lose out on $22.6 billion to Social Security and $5.7 billion to Medicare in annual contributions.

Name: Jayapal, Pramila
text:
So, in sum ‚Äî immigrants are VITAL to this country.

A mass deportation would not only cruelly rip apart millions of families, but it would cost our country billions and devastate our economy.

Trump‚Äôs Project 2025 is bad for America ‚Äî it‚Äôs that simple.

Name: Ossoff, Jon
text:
GEORGIA: Do you need help accessing resources after Hurricane Helene? 

Visit our Resource Guide to find step-by-step instructions for how to apply for @fema Individual Assistance, @SBAgov loans, @USDA programs, and more at https://t.co/74YaEFgXqk, or read more below:

Name: Ossoff, Jon
text: .@fema's Individual Assistance Program provides financial and direct services to eligible individuals and households affected by a disaster, who have uninsured or under-insured necessary expenses and serious needs.

Name: Ossoff, Jon
text:
How to Apply for @fema Individual Assistance?

1. Visit https://t.co/MPdXjSkmk4

2. Or call the FEMA Hotline at 1-800-621-3362. 

3. Or download the FEMA app to submit your application: https://t.co/xLvM7d3iui

Name: Ossoff, Jon
text:
Apply for @fema Individual Assistance:

1. Visit https://t.co/6Kz9jwZiC1 & click ‚Äúlet‚Äôs get started‚Äù to check if you are eligible. (or call FEMA Hotline at 1-800-621-3362)

2. Get Personal Info: Mailing & email addresses; phone #; Social Security # (SSN); banking & insurance info

Name: Ossoff, Jon
text:
.@fema's Individual Assistance Program is not a substitute for insurance and cannot compensate for all losses caused by a disaster. 

The assistance is intended to meet basic needs and supplement disaster recovery efforts.

Name: Ossoff, Jon
text:
Apply for @fema Individual Assistance:

3. Fill Out Application: Enter as much detail as you can. You can go back later to enter anything you don‚Äôt have now.

Name: Ossoff, Jon
text:
Apply for @fema Individual Assistance:

4. Review & Submit: Check what you‚Äôve entered, make changes if you need to, and send your application to FEMA. Remember to save and keep your Application ID. 

You‚Äôll need it anytime you talk with FEMA.

Name: Ossoff, Jon
text: .@fema's Individual Assistance program offers Federal funding for individuals impacted by natural disasters, including for those who incur housing costs, food costs, and for other vital supplies. This may include:

Name: Ossoff, Jon
text:
-Accessibility Needs: Money to help survivors with a disability with specific repairs to make sure their home is accessible, such as exterior ramp, grab bars, and paved path to the home entrance.

Visit https://t.co/MPdXjSkmk4 to learn more.

Name: Ossoff, Jon
text:
-Rental Assistance:¬†Money you can use to rent housing if you are displaced from your home because of the disaster.

-Lodging Expense Reimbursement: Money to reimburse you for emergency lodging expenses, such as hotel or motel, if you are displaced from your home.

Name: Ossoff, Jon
text:
-Home Repair or Replacement:¬†Money to help you repair or replace your home damaged by the disaster. The money can also help with pre-existing damage to parts of your home where the disaster caused further damage.

Visit https://t.co/MPdXjSkmk4 to learn more.

Name: Ossoff, Jon
text:
Immediate Needs:¬†Money to help you pay for immediate needs such as water, food, first aid, prescriptions, infant formula, breastfeeding equipment, diapers, personal hygiene items and fuels for transportation.

Visit https://t.co/MPdXjSkmk4 to learn more.

Name: Ossoff, Jon
text: Personal Property: Money to help you repair or replace appliances, room furnishings, & a personal or family computer damaged by the disaster. This can also include money for books, uniforms, tools, computers & other items required for school or work, including self-employment.

Name: Ossoff, Jon
text:
Displacement:¬†Money to help with immediate housing needs if you cannot return to your home because of the disaster. The money can be used to stay in a hotel, with family and friends or other options while you look for a rental unit.

Visit https://t.co/MPdXjSkmk4 to learn more.

Name: Ossoff, Jon
text: Medical/Dental:¬†Money to help you pay for expenses because the disaster caused an injury or illness. This money can also be used to help replace medical/dental equipment, breastfeeding equipment, or prescribed medicine damaged or lost because of the disaster.

Name: Ossoff, Jon
text:
Childcare: Money to help you pay for increased or unplanned for childcare expenses caused by the disaster.

Transportation:¬†Money to help you repair or replace a vehicle damaged by the disaster when you don‚Äôt have another vehicle you can use.

Name: Ossoff, Jon
text:
Moving and Storage Expenses: Money to help you move and store personal property from your home to prevent additional damage, usually while you are making repairs to your home or moving to a new place due to the disaster.

Visit https://t.co/MPdXjSkmk4 to learn more.

Name: Ossoff, Jon
text:
What Happens After You Apply to @fema's Individual Assistance Program: 

1. FEMA Reviews Your App: If FEMA can‚Äôt qualify you based on your application alone, they may request more info.

2. Check Your Email: FEMA will email you when you have messages on your account.

Name: Ossoff, Jon
text:
3. Check Your Status: You can sign in to your account at any time to check the status of your application.

4. Get Payment: If you qualify, FEMA will send a payment using the method you choose, either through direct deposit or a check my mail.

Name: Ossoff, Jon
text:
For more questions,

1. Visit https://t.co/MPdXjSjOuw

2. Or call the FEMA Hotline at 1-800-621-3362.

3. Or download the FEMA app to get help: https://t.co/xLvM7d2KEK

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
This week, I sat down with representatives from Bucks County Opportunity Council, @Philabundance, @Housing4All, @rollingharvest, MontCo Anti-Hunger Network, @FeedingPA, and Bucks County Government for an important roundtable conversation on food insecurity in our community and the critical challenges community members face in accessing the nourishment they need to thrive.

Their frontline insights were invaluable as we discussed ways to strengthen our efforts in combating food insecurity. This issue transcends politics, which is why since entering Congress, I‚Äôve made this a top-priority to address. Just last week, we secured a major victory through a bipartisan effort I led to extend protections for victims of food stamp theft, ensuring that thousands of families relying on SNAP can continue to access food without fear of losing their benefits.

Thank you to these incredible advocates for your dedication to bringing about meaningful change in our community and for sharing your thoughtful insights. I look forward to continuing our partnership in this shared mission to ensure every PA-1 resident has access to the food and support they need and deserve.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1962, ùê∑ùëü. ùëÅùëú, the inaugural film in the James Bond series featuring Sean Connery, premieres in London. 

Directed by Terence Young and based on the novel by Ian Fleming, the plot centers on Bond's mission to investigate the disappearance of a fellow British agent in Jamaica, leading him to the secretive lair of Dr. Julius No, who is devising a plot to disrupt an American space launch using a radio beam weapon.

ùê∑ùëü. ùëÅùëú was made on a low budget but became a financial success, paving the way for future installments. While it received mixed reviews upon release, it has since earned a reputation as one of the best films in the series. Notably, it introduced significant elements that became trademarks of the Bond franchise, including the distinctive gun barrel opening sequence, the stylized title sequence, and the iconic theme music.

The film also set the stage for the visual style of the series with elaborate sets that enhanced the storytelling. Additionally, ùê∑ùëü. ùëÅùëú incorporated references to earlier and later works in Fleming's series, including the criminal organization SPECTRE, which would play a prominent role in subsequent films.

The film's success led to a flourishing genre of secret agent films in the 1960s, as well as adaptations like comic books and soundtrack albums, further solidifying its cultural impact. Following ùê∑ùëü. ùëÅùëú, the next film in the series, ùêπùëüùëúùëö ùëÖùë¢ùë†ùë†ùëñùëé ùë§ùëñùë°‚Ñé ùêøùëúùë£ùëí, was released in 1963, continuing the legacy of James Bond in cinema.

Recorded: Wednesday, April 3, 2024

Reflecting on the first anniversary of the October 7 surprise terrorist attack against Israel, we take you behind the scenes of our congressional delegation trip to Israel last April and share what it was like to witness firsthand the devastating sites of the October 7 terrorist attacks. 

We also discuss how it feels to be in Israel, walking among the same places as the people we read about in the Bible and the religious figures we admire and look up to.

üö® Just talked to @NHC_Atlantic Director Dr. Mike Brennan. Here are the 3 things they want Floridians to know about Tropical Storm #Milton: 

üåÄ MAKE A PLAN NOW

üåÄ MAJOR & MASSIVE HURRICANE

üåÄ WATCH FOR EVACUATION ORDERS

More here ‚¨áÔ∏è

üîò MAKE A PLAN - the track could shift, but the storm is expected to be BIG. The entire Gulf Coast needs to be ready for landfall on Wednesday and make a plan NOW.

üîò MAJOR HURRICANE - this is expected to be a massive major hurricane that could bring storm surge, torrential rain, flooding and power outages to huge portions of our state. NHC expects Milton to exit the east coast still at hurricane strength. Central Florida and the First, Space and Treasure Coasts need to take this seriously. 

üîò KNOW WHERE TO EVACUATE - if you are placed under a mandatory evacuation order - GET OUT. REMEMBER‚Ä¶if asked to evacuate, you don‚Äôt have to go hours away. Just get to the nearest shelter. Keep your family safe!

America must embrace Israel‚Äôs efforts to destroy these terrorist organizations and build a future with like-minded allies, especially those in the Muslim world, to bring peace, stability, and prosperity to the people that these authoritarian fanatics have terrorized for generations.

Coached by John Heisman‚Äîafter whom the Heisman Trophy is named‚ÄîGeorgia Tech surged to a 63-0 lead in the first quarter at Grant Field in Atlanta. Heisman opted to shorten the quarters to 12 minutes, yet speculation arose that he ran up the score as revenge for Cumberland allegedly using professional players to defeat Georgia Tech in baseball.

Cumberland player Ed Haysler Poague later remarked that while his team wasn't bad, they were ‚Äúso ridiculously outclassed that day that it was, well, ridiculous.‚Äù Fans quickly realized the game wouldn't be competitive, leading to laughter in the stands. The Atlanta Constitution noted that ‚Äúall of Cumberland's plays were smothered completely.‚Äù Despite leading 126-0 at halftime, Heisman urged his players to maintain their intensity in the second half, stating, ‚ÄúYou never know what those Cumberland players have up their sleeve.‚Äù

Name: Curtis, John R.
text:
One year since the deadliest attack on the Jewish people since the Holocaust, the grief and horror from that day‚Äîand the days that followed‚Äîremain unimaginable. I want to reiterate my unwavering support for the State of Israel, its defense of its people, and the return of the hostages who have endured a year in darkness, facing unimaginable torture, starvation, and abuse. We must find a solution that brings them home and dismantles Iran‚Äôs terror network and its proxies.
¬†
What often gets lost in this conflict is the ongoing fragility Israel has faced throughout its existence. While Americans have come to know Israel as relatively secure over the past two decades, especially with the normalization of ties with Arab nations, it wasn‚Äôt always this way. I lived in Israel in 1978, before the peace brought by President Carter, Egyptian President Anwar Sadat, and Israeli Prime Minister Menachem Begin. That peace was real and impactful.
¬†
In recent weeks, Israel has brought to justice those who have harmed not only their nation but our citizens, too. That alone should solidify the United States‚Äô deep and unwavering support.
¬†
As we commemorate this heartbreaking day, I want the Jewish people to know I stand with them, always. In their mourning, I mourn. In their peace and prosperity, I share their joy.
¬†
May there be abundant peace from heaven, and life, for us and all Israel. #utpol

Name: Schiff, Adam B.
text:
One year ago, Hamas launched a horrific mass terrorist attack on Israel.

Nearly 1,200 were killed ‚Äì most of them civilians. Families were torn apart as Hamas indiscriminately launched rockets at kibbutzim and dragged hostages into Gaza.

Hamas terrorists committed unspeakable crimes against women and children in what was the darkest, most deadly day in Israel‚Äôs history. Raping, torturing and murdering its victims.¬†
¬†
A year later, there are still hostages held in tunnels under Gaza, including seven Americans ‚Äì Keith Siegel, Edan Alexander, Omer Neutra, Itay Chen, Sagui Dekel-Chen, Gadi Haggai, and Judith Weinstein Haggai.

The families of these hostages still don‚Äôt know whether their loved ones will ever come home, and every day without their release brings a fresh trauma.

Hamas‚Äô use of Palestinians as human shields continues to put the lives of innocent civilians at risk and exacts a terrible toll.¬†
¬†
A year later ‚Äì as we continue to grieve and grapple with the terror of that day ‚Äì we must recommit ourselves to bringing every hostage home; to securing a close to this conflict that ensures the end of Hamas as a governing entity or military threat; that allows Israelis to return to their homes without being shelled by Hezbollah; and that provides for the long-term safety and security of Palestinians as well.¬†
¬†
The United States‚Äô alliance with Israel is unbreakable.

Our commitment to our ally‚Äôs security and defense remains ironclad.

We must continue to work to ensure the horrors of October 7th can never be repeated.

Name: Owens, Burgess
text:
One year ago today was the deadliest day for the Jewish People since the Holocaust. Thousands of innocent civilians were murdered, hundreds of women and children were raped and butchered by Hamas terrorists, while hundreds more were dragged back to Gaza in chains.

Today, 97 hostages‚Äîincluding 5 Americans‚Äîremain captives of Hamas while Iran continues to prop up terrorist groups and launch missiles with the express goal of destroying Israel.

The United States will continue to lead with moral clarity and support Israel unequivocally in its mission to destroy evil, protect its people, and ensure the safe return of all hostages.

My full statement with the Utah Congressional Delegation:

This October 7th, we, the Utah Congressional Delegation, acknowledge and condemn the evil and depraved act of terrorism inflicted on the Israeli people by Hamas one year ago today. We call for the immediate return of all hostages held by Hamas and stand with those fighting the scourge of antisemitism in our world.

We pray for the return of the seven American citizens still being held hostage by Hamas at this very hour. We call for Hamas to immediately return all remaining hostages to their families with immediate effect.

We note that members of our delegation have met with family members who lost loved ones at the Nova Festival, and the many villages and cities near the Gaza border. We have met with hostage families and stand behind them both in action and in prayer.

We acknowledge that Israel remains one of our most important regional allies and a country with which we as Americans share much in common, and that this premeditated attack was acutely felt in Utah and across the United States.

We remain concerned over the increase of antisemitism in America over the past year, with rhetoric on our college campuses delving into gross tropes, conspiracies, synagogues, and houses of worship threatened with violence, even here in Utah.

We declare that the true intentions of the authoritarian regime in Iran are to destroy the state of Israel and sow chaos in the region through an extensive proxy network.

We continue our efforts to promote strong American leadership that rejects antisemitism at home and abroad, ends accommodation efforts with Iran, and supports the defense and security of the state of Israel.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
One year ago today, the world witnessed a day of unimaginable horror. On October 7th, Hamas launched a brutal and unprovoked assault on innocent civilians in Israel, including Americans, marking the deadliest day for the Jewish people since the Holocaust. This grim anniversary serves as a solemn reminder of the families torn apart, communities devastated, and the deep wounds that still linger. Yet even in the face of such unspeakable tragedy, one truth remains steadfast: Israel will endure, and those who seek its destruction will never prevail.
 
In the two months following this heinous attack, antisemitic incidents in the U.S. surged by 358% compared to the previous year. A year later, this pattern of hatred and violence continues to rise across the world. We cannot‚Äîand will not‚Äîallow antisemitism to become normalized. We cannot let terror take root.
 
As Co-Chair of the Bipartisan Task Force for Combating Antisemitism, it is my mission to ensure our friends in Israel and our Jewish communities here in America and around the world are not just supported but protected‚Äîunequivocally and without hesitation. I have, and will always, push forward and champion initiatives to confront the scourge of antisemitism at every level‚Äîfrom our campuses to the global stage‚Äîbecause this hatred, in all its forms, must be met with unwavering rejection and decisive action.
 
Today, as we remember the victims of October 7th, we renew our vow to be relentless in the fight against terrorism and antisemitism and to stand unwaveringly with our friends in Israel, always. Though hatred seeks to divide us, the resilience of the human spirit and the strength of our shared values will prevail. Together, we will ensure democracy, freedom, justice, and peace triumph.

text:
Today marks the solemn one-year anniversary of Hamas' barbaric attack on Israel, which claimed the lives of 1,200 innocent people. This unprovoked act of terror reminds us of the ongoing threats Israel faces on many fronts, and we continue to stand in unwavering solidarity with our closest ally in the Middle East.
¬†
Israel has every right to defend itself, and the United States must fully support their efforts to eliminate Hamas, Hezbollah, and other Iranian-backed proxies, all menaces to the region. The release of hostages remains a top priority, and the world should recognize the incredible courage and resilience of the Israeli people.
¬†
As we reflect on this tragedy, we also have to redouble our efforts to combat the rise of anti-Semitism around the world. Hatred and violence against the Jewish people have no place in any society, and we need to work together to put an end to these dangerous ideologies.
¬†
Our prayers remain with the victims and their families. The United States will always stand with Israel, and we must continue to ensure that such acts of terror are never repeated.

October 7th was the deadliest day for the Jewish people since the Holocaust. I‚Äôve met with Israelis and Americans whose loved ones were brutally killed by Hamas, and I‚Äôve held parents whose children were violently taken as hostages. People are experiencing deep pain. Israel has the right to defend itself from terrorist attacks, and we must bring these hostages home.

Instead of securing the release of the hostages, however, Prime Minister Netanyahu has unleashed unthinkable violence on innocent civilians in Gaza. More than a million Palestinians are facing starvation. We see videos of dead children held in the arms of their parents. Violence is escalating throughout the region, including most recently in Lebanon, threatening even more human suffering.

This cycle of violence won't make anyone safer. The United States must commit to upholding human rights, international law, and accountability for the use of U.S. weapons. text:
One year ago, the world watched in horror as Hamas terrorists unleashed a monstrous assault on Israel. During their brutality on October 7th, Hamas slaughtered nearly 1,200 people, including more than forty Americans, wounded thousands more, and kidnapped hundreds of civilian adults and children.

This horrific attack, orchestrated by a terrorist organization dedicated to the destruction of the State of Israel, was the deadliest massacre of Jews since the Holocaust. text:
Joint statement from the House-Knesset Parliamentary Friendship Group to mark one-year since Hamas terrorist attack on Israel:

One year ago today, barbaric Hamas terrorists invaded Israel and murdered over 1200 innocent men, women, and children, including over 40 Americans, and took over 250 hostages. That morning, the world changed forever.

On October 7, 2023, people were slaughtered, burned alive, raped, and kidnapped. However, this day is not only defined by grief and loss, but also a testament to human strength, unity, and solidarity. Terrorism does not distinguish between religions, nationalities, or ethnicities. It targets humanity. 
  
The United States and Israel are unified in our effort to strengthen regional stability, counter terrorism, and increase security. In recent years, the partnership between our two nations has only grown stronger.  
  
The House-Knesset Parliamentary Friendship Group will continue to work together to combat terror organizations that have called for the elimination of the State of Israel, and further wish to end democracy and destabilize the free world. 
  
The world must never forget the atrocities that occurred on October 7th, and the innocent victims who lost their lives. We will not rest until all the hostages are returned home, Hamas and Hezbollah are defeated, and Iran stands down.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1962, North Korea held parliamentary elections for the 3rd Supreme People's Assembly, where voter turnout was reported at a remarkable 100%, with all votes cast in favor of the candidates.

In North Korea, voting is mandatory, and there is no opportunity for dissent. All citizens aged 17 and older must participate, often facing pressure to show loyalty by arriving early and joining lengthy queues. The voting process involves receiving a ballot with a single name, which voters drop into a publicly visible ballot box. Although there is a private voting booth available, using it could lead to suspicion from authorities.

Once voters leave the polling station, they are expected to join cheering groups outside, publicly expressing enthusiasm for the leadership. State media portray election days as festive occasions, with celebrations surrounding polling stations. In addition to serving as a mechanism for political control, these elections also function as a census, enabling authorities to monitor the population in each constituency and track any potential defectors fleeing to China.

Overall, North Korea's electoral process reflects the regime's strict control over political life, ensuring total compliance and the appearance of unanimous support for the ruling Kim family dynasty.

Name: Buchanan, Vern
text:
Just wrapped up a call with Governor DeSantis and the Florida Division of Emergency Management Director in preparation for Hurricane Milton.
 
As the governor mentioned, the storm has been more unpredictable than Hurricane Helene and will directly impact much of our area, bringing winds of up to 130 mph and storm surge of up to 15 feet.
 
This will likely lead to massive power outages affecting millions. However, the governor assured me that 40,000 linemen are standing by to help restore power. 
 
Furthermore, there are 8,000 National Guardsmen, Florida State Guardsmen and local officials ready to assist those in need.
 
Lastly, while we are hearing reports of gas stations running out of fuel, the governor clarified that there is not a shortage but rather a distribution problem and they are working to address it as soon as possible.
